# **![][image1]** **Gemini RAG ‚Äì Hallucination & Cost Control Project**

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ **Introduction**

This project implements a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) system with a strong focus on:

* Reducing hallucinations  
* Optimizing token usage  
* Controlling inference cost  
* Maintaining acceptable latency

The system uses structured FAQ data, performs retrieval \+ reranking, generates answers using an LLM, and continuously evaluates faithfulness, tokens, and latency via a live dashboard.

---

2Ô∏è‚É£ **Why is This Project Useful?**

Large Language Models (LLMs) are powerful but have three major production risks:

1. ‚ùå Hallucinations (confident but wrong answers)  
2. üí∞ High token cost  
3. ‚è±Ô∏è Slow response time (latency)

This project addresses all three by:

* Grounding answers in your own data  
* Reducing unnecessary tokens  
* Measuring and optimizing system performance

üëâ This makes the system trustworthy, scalable, and cost-effective.

---

3Ô∏è‚É£ **How Does the RAG Pipeline Work?**

### **RAG Flow** üîÑ

### **User Question ‚Üí Retriever (Vector Search) ‚Üí Reranker (Precision Filtering) ‚Üí LLM (Grounded Generation) ‚Üí Self-Correction & Metrics**

### 

### **![][image2]**

### 

### **Step-by-step**

1. **Retriever**  
   * Converts user query into embeddings  
   * Retrieves top-K relevant chunks from the dataset  
2. **Reranker**  
   * Re-scores retrieved chunks  
   * Keeps only the most relevant context  
3. **Generator**  
   * Sends system prompt \+ context \+ question to LLM  
   * Generates answer strictly from context  
4. **Evaluator**  
   * Checks faithfulness  
   * Calculates hallucination risk  
   * Logs tokens & latency

Read More:- [Link](https://github.com/Manuhd/RAG/blob/main/README.md)

# 4Ô∏è‚É£ What Happened After Implementing Reranker? ![][image3]**Before Reranker ‚ùå** Multiple chunks sent to LLM‚Üí more tokens, more noise, higher hallucination risk

### **After Reranker ‚úÖ** Only top-1/2 chunks ‚Üí cleaner context, lower token usage, better faithfulness, faster response

### **Result**

| Metric | Impact |
| ----- | ----- |
| Retrieved tokens | ‚¨á Reduced |
| Cost | ‚¨á Reduced |
| Hallucination | ‚¨á Reduced |
| Latency | ‚¨Ü Improved |

üëâ Reranker trades a small compute cost for major LLM savings

---

5Ô∏è‚É£ **How Is Hallucination Controlled?**

Hallucination is reduced using **multiple layers**:

* **RAG grounding:** LLM answers only from retrieved context  
* **System guardrails:** If information is missing, respond with *‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know‚Äù*  
* **Faithfulness scoring:** Verifies answer support from context  
* **Self-correction:** Ungrounded answers fall back to safe responses

üëâ The system prefers **safety over wrong answers**, which is **production-grade behavior**.

**6Ô∏è‚É£ How Is Token Size Reduced?**

Token usage is optimized at multiple stages:

* **Ingestion:** Small row-based chunks (1 FAQ \= 1 chunk), no overlap, no extra metadata

* **Query Time:** Reranker limits context, short system prompt, only relevant content sent

* **Visibility:** Tokens tracked separately (system, question, retrieved, output)

![][image4]

**üßÆ Token Usage Distribution (Per Query)**

The pie chart shows how tokens are typically consumed across stages:

* **System Tokens** ‚Äì fixed instructions (system prompt)  
* **Question Tokens** ‚Äì user input  
* **Retrieved Tokens** ‚Äì context passed after retrieval \+ reranking (**largest cost driver**)  
* **Output Tokens** ‚Äì model-generated answer

üëâ This visualization clearly highlights **why reranking and context reduction matter most**‚Äîretrieved tokens dominate overall usage.

###  **7Ô∏è‚É£ What Happens After Implementing Cache?**

* **Without cache‚ùå:** Every repeated question triggers the full pipeline, causing repeated LLM calls and higher cost

* **With cache‚úÖ:** Repeated questions are served instantly with no LLM call, near-zero cost, and very low latency

**Cached items:** final answer, token stats, and faithfulness score

üëâ Cache converts **O(n) LLM cost into O(1) lookup**.

![][image5]

8Ô∏è‚É£ **How to Reduce Cost (Production-Ready Approach)**

Cost reduction is achieved by design, not by luck.

### üí∞ **Cost Control Techniques**

| Technique | Effect |
| ----- | ----- |
| RAG | Avoids training/fine-tuning |
| Reranker | Reduces context tokens |
| Small chunks | Lower embedding cost |
| Short prompts | Lower system tokens |
| Token tracking | Cost transparency |
| Cache (future) | Zero-cost repeat queries |

### **Final Outcome**

Cost scales linearly with usage, not exponentially.

This project demonstrates **production-ready GenAI engineering** focused on **trust, measurement, and optimization**‚Äîprioritizing reduced hallucination, controlled cost, and acceptable latency.

**Everything else is secondary.**

**Tech Stack & Frameworks**

The project uses Python with Streamlit, FAISS, and Gemini, implementing a modular RAG architecture with embedding-based retrieval, reranking, and evaluation.

| Category | Framework / Library | Purpose |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Programming Language | Python 3.x | Core language for the entire RAG pipeline |
| Web UI Framework | Streamlit | Interactive dashboard for Q\&A, metrics, tokens, and latency |
| Vector Search | FAISS | In-memory vector similarity search for retrieval |
| Data Processing | Pandas | CSV loading, preprocessing, logging |
| Numerical Computing | NumPy | Vector and similarity operations |
| Environment Management | python-dotenv | Secure handling of API keys |
| Time Measurement | time (Python stdlib) | End-to-end latency measurement |
| Logging | csv (Python stdlib) | File-based logging of queries and metrics |

| Model Type | Model Name | Usage |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Large Language Model (LLM) | Google Gemini (Flash / Pro) | Answer generation |
| Embedding Model | Sentence Embedding Model | Converts text into vector embeddings |
| Reranker Model | Lightweight similarity-based reranker | Re-scores retrieved chunks for precision |

**General Guidelines for Acceptable Rates**

| Use Case  | Risk Level | Target Hallucination Rate | Why? |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Medical/Clinical Decision Support** | Very High | \< 1% | Inaccuracies can directly impact patient diagnosis and safety. A study on clinical note generation achieved a **1.47%** rate for all hallucinations, with major errors below human note-taking rates. |
| **Legal/Financial Advice** | High | \< 5% | False information can lead to severe financial or legal consequences, including lawsuits. Some services claim 100% accuracy, but real-world testing shows current rates can be much higher (e.g., 35% in one study). |
| **Enterprise/Business Intelligence (RAG)** | Medium | \< 5% | For internal sales or general business tools, a rate under **5%** is generally ideal to maintain trust and prevent misinformed decisions. Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) systems can help achieve this by grounding responses in verified internal documents. |
| **General Information/Customer Service** | Low to Medium | 5‚Äì10% | While accuracy is important, minor errors are less critical. The focus is on providing helpful, contextually relevant information most of the time. |
| **Creative Writing/Entertainment** | Low | Higher rates are acceptable | Factual accuracy is not the primary goal; imaginative, even fabricated content is part of the desired output. |

Key Considerations

* **Impact of Errors:** A "major" hallucination that causes significant harm must be virtually eliminated, whereas a minor, easily correctable error is less critical.  
* **Trust and Adoption:** Even in low-risk scenarios, a consistently high hallucination rate (e.g., 15-20%) erodes user trust and prevents the successful adoption of the AI system.  
* **Mitigation Works:** Techniques like RAG and multi-agent verification can significantly reduce rates (by 60-80%), making lower rates achievable for most applications. 

Ultimately, the goal for most professional applications is to get as close to **0% hallucination as possible** in production environments.
